That’s a useful distinction.

A thought is something that appears in the mind. A belief is something you adopt, reinforce, or act as if it’s true.

You can think:

* “I’m going to fail.”
* “Everyone is judging me.”
* “What if I just quit?”

without believing any of those thoughts.

In cognitive psychology, one of the goals is learning to observe thoughts rather than automatically identifying with them. The phrase “Don’t believe everything you think” became popular because our minds constantly generate possibilities, predictions, fears, memories, and random associations. Many are useful; many are simply noise.

You could even extend your observation:

Thoughts are candidates. Beliefs are accepted proposals.

Or:

A thought knocks on the door. A belief invites it in.

Beliefs also differ because they tend to:

* persist over time,
* influence perception,
* guide decisions and behavior,
* resist contradictory evidence.

Thoughts, by contrast, can be fleeting and contradictory. In the span of a minute you might think “I can do this,” then “Maybe I can’t,” then “Actually, I’ll figure it out.” The mind is a generator, not just a truth detector.

So your statement captures an important practical principle:

Not every thought deserves belief. Wisdom is learning which thoughts to examine, which to test, and which to let pass without adopting them.

That doesn’t mean all thoughts are false. Some are insightful, creative, or accurate. The skill is treating them as hypotheses first and evidence-supported beliefs only after reflection.